-- =============================================
-- 1. Starting a Business
-- =============================================
(
  'how-to-register-as-sole-trader-uk',
  'How to Register as a Sole Trader in the UK (Step-by-Step Guide)',
  'Registering as a sole trader is simpler than most people think. Here''s exactly how to do it, what it costs, and the deadlines you need to know.',
  E'## What Is a Sole Trader?\n\nA sole trader is the simplest way to run a business in the UK. You''re self-employed and responsible for your own tax and National Insurance. There''s no legal separation between you and your business — you personally own everything, including any debts.\n\nThis is the starting point for most freelancers, tradespeople, and small business owners in the UK. It''s quick to set up, inexpensive to run, and gives you complete control.\n\n## Do You Need to Register?\n\nYes — if you earn more than £1,000 from self-employment in a tax year, HMRC requires you to register as a sole trader and file a Self Assessment tax return.\n\nEven if you earn under £1,000, you might want to register to:\n- Prove self-employment (e.g. for mortgage applications)\n- Claim certain benefits or tax reliefs\n- Build a track record for future financing\n\n## Step 1: Choose a Business Name\n\nYou can trade under your own name, or choose a business name. If you choose a trading name, it cannot:\n- Include "Limited", "Ltd", "PLC", or "LLP"\n- Be offensive\n- Be the same as an existing trademark\n\nYou don''t need to register your sole trader name anywhere — but it''s worth checking the trademark database and Companies House to avoid conflicts.\n\n## Step 2: Register with HMRC\n\nThis is the main step. You need to register for Self Assessment by 5 October following the end of the tax year you started trading.\n\nFor example: if you started trading in June 2024 (in the 2024/25 tax year), you must register by 5 October 2025.\n\n**How to register:**\n\n1. Go to [www.gov.uk/register-for-self-assessment](https://www.gov.uk/register-for-self-assessment)\n2. Click "Register as a new sole trader"\n3. Sign in with or create a Government Gateway account\n4. Complete the online form (takes around 10 minutes)\n5. HMRC will send your Unique Taxpayer Reference (UTR) by post within 10 working days\n\n**What you''ll need:****\n- Your National Insurance number\n- Your date of birth\n- Your contact details\n- The date you started trading\n- A description of your business\n\n## Step 3: Set Up Your National Insurance\n\nAs a sole trader, you''ll pay Class 2 and Class 4 National Insurance through your Self Assessment return.\n\n- **Class 2**: £3.45 per week (if profits over £12,570)\n- **Class 4**: 9% on profits between £12,570 and £50,270; 2% above\n\nYou don''t need to set these up separately — they''re calculated when you file your tax return.\n\n## Step 4: Open a Business Bank Account (Optional but Recommended)\n\nYou''re not legally required to have a separate business bank account as a sole trader. But it makes your accounting much cleaner and simplifies your Self Assessment filing.\n\nGood options for sole traders in the UK:\n- **Monzo Business** — free tier, instant notifications\n- **Starling Bank** — no fees, excellent app\n- **Tide** — popular with freelancers and tradespeople\n\n## Step 5: Keep Records\n\nHMRC requires you to keep records of all your income and expenses for at least 5 years after the 31 January submission deadline.\n\nYou need to track:\n- All income received\n- Business expenses (more on this below)\n- Bank statements\n- Invoices and receipts\n\n## What Can You Claim as Expenses?\n\nAllowable business expenses reduce your taxable profit. Common ones for sole traders:\n\n| Expense | Examples |\n|---|---|\n| Office costs | Stationery, software subscriptions |\n| Travel | Fuel, train tickets (business only) |\n| Equipment | Tools, laptop, phone (business proportion) |\n| Marketing | Website, advertising, business cards |\n| Professional fees | Accountant, legal advice |\n| Training | Courses, books relevant to your work |\n| Clothing | Uniforms or protective gear |\n\n**Working from home?** You can claim a proportion of your home expenses, or use HMRC''s flat rate: £10/month for 25+ hours worked at home per month.\n\n## Self Assessment Deadlines\n\nOnce registered, you''ll file a Self Assessment tax return every year:\n\n- **31 January**: Online return filed AND tax paid\n- **31 July**: Second payment on account (if applicable)\n- **5 October**: Register by this date for new sole traders\n\nMiss these and you''ll face automatic penalties starting at £100.\n\n## When Should You Consider Going Limited?\n\nA sole trader structure works well up to roughly £30,000–£40,000 profit. Above that, the tax savings from operating as a limited company often outweigh the extra admin costs.\n\nOur [Sole Trader vs Limited Company Calculator](/tools/sole-trader-vs-limited) shows you the exact tax difference at your income level.\n\n## Summary: Sole Trader Registration Checklist\n\n- [ ] Choose a business name\n- [ ] Register with HMRC for Self Assessment (by 5 October)\n- [ ] Get your UTR number\n- [ ] Open a business bank account\n- [ ] Set up a record-keeping system\n- [ ] Know your Self Assessment deadlines\n\nThat''s it. The whole process takes about 20 minutes online, and you''ll be fully registered within two weeks.\n\n---\n\n*Need help getting your business set up from scratch? Our [Launchpad checklist](/launchpad) walks you through every step — from registering to launching your first marketing campaign.*',
  'starting-a-business',
  ARRAY['sole trader', 'HMRC', 'self assessment', 'registration', 'self-employed'],
  'Akin Yavuz',
  true,
  now() - interval '30 days',
  'How to Register as a Sole Trader UK — Step-by-Step Guide 2025',
  'Complete guide to registering as a sole trader in the UK. Learn exactly what to do, when to register with HMRC, and what records to keep.',
  8
),

