-- 2. Starting a Business
-- =============================================
(
  'sole-trader-vs-limited-company-which-is-right-for-you',
  'Sole Trader vs Limited Company: Which Is Right for You?',
  'The structure you choose affects your tax bill, your liability, and how seriously clients take you. Here''s how to decide.',
  E'## The Most Important Business Decision You''ll Make Early On\n\nWhen you start a business in the UK, the first real decision is how to structure it: sole trader or limited company?\n\nBoth are legitimate, widely-used structures. The right choice depends on your profit level, your risk tolerance, your long-term plans, and how much admin you''re willing to deal with.\n\nThis guide breaks it all down — with numbers.\n\n## What''s the Difference?\n\n### Sole Trader\n\nYou and your business are the same legal entity. Simple to set up, minimal filing requirements, but:\n- Your personal assets are at risk if the business can''t pay its debts\n- You pay Income Tax and National Insurance on all profits\n- Tax rates can hit 40% at higher incomes\n\n### Limited Company\n\nA limited company is a separate legal entity. You''re a director (and often shareholder). This means:\n- Personal liability is limited to what you''ve invested\n- Tax is paid at corporation tax rates (19–25%) rather than income tax rates\n- You can take a salary + dividends, which is often more tax-efficient\n- More admin: annual accounts, confirmation statement, corporation tax return\n\n## The Tax Comparison\n\nLet''s look at the numbers for someone earning £60,000 profit.\n\n### Sole Trader at £60,000\n\n| | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| Taxable profit | £60,000 |\n| Income tax | £11,432 |\n| NI Class 2 | £180 |\n| NI Class 4 | £3,373 |\n| **Total tax** | **£14,985** |\n| **Take-home** | **£45,015** |\n\n### Limited Company at £60,000\n\nOptimal strategy: pay yourself a salary of £9,100 (NI threshold), take rest as dividends.\n\n| | Amount |\n|---|---|\n| Corporation tax (on profit after salary) | £9,691 |\n| Income tax on salary | £0 |\n| Dividend tax | £3,054 |\n| **Total tax** | **£12,745** |\n| **Take-home** | **£47,255** |\n\n**Limited company saves you ~£2,240 at £60,000 profit.**\n\nFor an instant comparison at your income level, use our [Sole Trader vs Limited Company Calculator](/tools/sole-trader-vs-limited).\n\n## At What Point Does It Make Sense to Go Limited?\n\nAs a rough rule:\n\n- **Under £30,000**: Stay sole trader. The tax saving doesn''t justify the extra admin cost.\n- **£30,000–£50,000**: Borderline. Run the numbers for your specific situation.\n- **Over £50,000**: The tax saving usually justifies going limited. A good accountant pays for themselves.\n\nOther factors that push you toward limited earlier:\n- You want to reinvest profits in the business (leave money in the company and you only pay 19–25% corp tax, not personal income tax)\n- You''re raising investment (investors expect shares in a company)\n- You''re contracting for large businesses (many require limited company status)\n- You want to protect personal assets (limited liability)\n\n## The Admin Comparison\n\n| Task | Sole Trader | Limited Company |\n|---|---|---|\n| Setup | Register with HMRC online | Register with Companies House (£50) |\n| Annual tax return | Self Assessment (once/year) | Corporation tax return + self assessment |\n| Accounts | No formal requirement | Full accounts filed at Companies House |\n| Confirmation statement | Not required | £34/year |\n| Accounting costs | £300–£600/year | £800–£1,500/year |\n\n## What About IR35?\n\nIf you''re a contractor, IR35 is worth understanding. HMRC''s "off-payroll working rules" mean that if you''re effectively an employee of a client, you lose the tax benefits of a limited company structure.\n\nThis is particularly relevant for IT contractors and consultants working with large businesses. Get advice before incorporating if this applies to you.\n\n## Making the Switch\n\nIf you start as a sole trader and later want to go limited, it''s not complicated:\n\n1. Register the company at Companies House (takes ~24 hours online)\n2. Open a business bank account in the company name\n3. Notify HMRC your sole trader business has ceased\n4. Register the company for corporation tax (within 3 months of starting to trade)\n\nYou can transfer assets and client contracts to the new company, though some contracts may need to be re-signed.\n\n## The Verdict\n\nFor most people just starting out, **sole trader is the right call**. It''s simple, cheap to run, and perfectly adequate below £40,000 profit.\n\nIf your profit is consistently above £50,000, seriously consider going limited. The tax savings are real, and a good accountant will cost far less than you save.\n\n---\n\n*Not sure which way to go? Try our [Sole Trader vs Limited Company Calculator](/tools/sole-trader-vs-limited) and see exactly how much you''d save — or start the [Business Launchpad](/launchpad) to get your setup right from the beginning.*',
  'starting-a-business',
  ARRAY['sole trader', 'limited company', 'tax', 'business structure', 'self-employed'],
  'Akin Yavuz',
  true,
  now() - interval '25 days',
  'Sole Trader vs Limited Company UK — Which Is Right for You?',
  'Sole trader or limited company? Compare the tax savings, liability protection, and admin burden with real numbers to find the right structure for your business.',
  9
),

