(
  'self-assessment-tax-return-guide-uk',
  'Self Assessment Tax Return: A Complete Guide for the Self-Employed',
  'Self Assessment trips up thousands of people every year. This guide covers everything — what to include, how to calculate your tax, and how to avoid penalties.',
  E'## Who Needs to File a Self Assessment Tax Return?\n\nIf any of the following apply to you in a tax year, you need to file:\n\n- You''re self-employed (sole trader or partner in a partnership)\n- You''re a company director\n- Your untaxed income exceeds £1,000\n- You earn more than £100,000\n- You have capital gains (selling shares, property, etc.)\n- You receive rental income over £2,500\n- You claim Child Benefit and you or your partner earn over £60,000\n\n## Key Dates\n\n| Deadline | What It Is |\n|---|---|\n| 5 April | End of the tax year |\n| 5 October | Register for Self Assessment if new |\n| 31 October | Paper return deadline |\n| 31 January | Online return filed AND tax paid |\n| 31 July | Second payment on account (if applicable) |\n\n**Miss 31 January** and you face an automatic £100 penalty — even if you don''t owe any tax.\n\n## What You''ll Need Before You Start\n\nGather these before you sit down to file:\n\n- Your Unique Taxpayer Reference (UTR)\n- National Insurance number\n- P60 (if you also have employment income)\n- Records of all self-employment income\n- Receipts and records of allowable expenses\n- Bank statements\n- Details of any other income (rental, investments, dividends)\n\n## Step-by-Step: Filing Your Return\n\n### Step 1: Log In to HMRC\n\nGo to gov.uk/log-in-file-self-assessment-tax-return and sign in with your Government Gateway credentials.\n\n### Step 2: Fill in the Basic Information\n\nYour name, address, NI number, UTR — the simple stuff.\n\n### Step 3: Self-Employment Section\n\nThis is the main event. You''ll enter:\n\n**Income**: Total turnover (all money you invoiced/received, before expenses)\n\n**Allowable expenses**: HMRC lets you deduct genuine business costs. The key categories:\n\n- Office, property and equipment\n- Car, van and travel\n- Clothing (uniforms/protective gear)\n- Staff costs (if you employ people)\n- Reselling goods\n- Legal and financial costs\n- Marketing, entertainment and subscriptions\n- Training costs\n\nAlternatively, if your turnover is under £85,000, you can use the **simplified expenses** method and just enter total income and total expenses without itemising.\n\n### Step 4: Calculate Taxable Profit\n\nTaxable profit = Turnover − Allowable expenses\n\nHMRC''s system calculates your tax automatically once you enter the figures.\n\n### Step 5: Other Income\n\nDeclare any other income: employment income, rental income, dividends, bank interest, etc.\n\n### Step 6: Claim Any Reliefs\n\nCommon reliefs to check:\n\n- **Personal allowance**: £12,570 tax-free (standard)\n- **Marriage allowance**: transfer up to £1,260 to a lower-earning spouse\n- **Pension contributions**: reduce taxable income\n- **Gift Aid**: extended basic rate band\n- **Trading allowance**: first £1,000 of income is tax-free\n\n### Step 7: Review and Submit\n\nHMRC shows you a tax calculation before you submit. Check it makes sense. Then submit.\n\n## Payments on Account\n\nIf your tax bill is over £1,000, HMRC requires you to make **payments on account** — essentially paying tax in advance for next year.\n\nYou''ll pay:\n- **31 January**: This year''s tax PLUS 50% of next year''s estimated tax\n- **31 July**: The remaining 50% of next year''s estimate\n\nThis trips up many first-time filers. If you file in January and owe £3,000, you''ll actually need to pay £4,500 that month (£3,000 + £1,500 payment on account).\n\nYou can apply to reduce payments on account if you expect your income to drop significantly.\n\n## Common Mistakes to Avoid\n\n**1. Forgetting mileage**\nYou can claim 45p per mile for the first 10,000 business miles, 25p after that. Most people forget half the trips they made.\n\n**2. Not claiming the home office allowance**\nIf you work from home, you can claim £10–£26/month using HMRC''s flat rate, depending on hours worked. Or calculate actual costs.\n\n**3. Missing the January deadline**\nThe penalty is £100 immediately, then £10/day after 3 months, then 5% of tax owed after 6 months. File even if you can''t pay — the filing penalty is separate from the payment penalty.\n\n**4. Mixing business and personal expenses**\nOnly claim expenses that are wholly and exclusively for business purposes.\n\n**5. Not keeping records**\nHMRC can investigate up to 7 years back. Keep everything.\n\n## How Much Tax Will You Pay?\n\nFor 2025/26:\n\n| Profit | Income Tax | NI | Total |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| £20,000 | £1,486 | £691 | £2,177 |\n| £35,000 | £4,486 | £2,041 | £6,527 |\n| £50,000 | £7,486 | £3,380 | £10,866 |\n| £80,000 | £19,432 | £3,940 | £23,372 |\n\nFor a precise figure at your income level, use our [Take-Home Pay Calculator](/tools/take-home-calculator).\n\n## Getting Help\n\nFor simple returns, you can absolutely file yourself using HMRC''s online system. If you have:\n- Multiple income sources\n- Rental income\n- Capital gains\n- Complex expenses\n- High income (over £100k)\n\n...it''s worth paying an accountant. A good one costs £300–£600/year for a sole trader and can save you far more in optimised deductions.\n\n---\n\n*Use our [Take-Home Pay Calculator](/tools/take-home-calculator) to estimate your tax before filing. Or start the [Business Launchpad](/launchpad) if you''re just setting up and want a checklist for everything.*',
  'tax-and-finance',
  ARRAY['self assessment', 'tax return', 'HMRC', 'sole trader', 'deadlines'],
  'Akin Yavuz',
  true,
  now() - interval '22 days',
  'Self Assessment Tax Return Guide UK — Complete 2025 Guide',
  'Everything you need to know about filing a Self Assessment tax return in the UK: who needs to file, key deadlines, how to calculate tax, and how to avoid penalties.',
  11
),

