(
  'vat-registration-guide-uk-small-business',
  'VAT Registration in the UK: When You Must Register and How',
  'VAT registration isn''t optional once you hit the threshold — but there are smart ways to manage it. Here''s what small business owners need to know.',
  E'## What Is VAT?\n\nValue Added Tax (VAT) is a consumption tax charged on most goods and services sold in the UK. The standard rate is 20%. As a VAT-registered business, you:\n\n- Charge VAT on your sales (output VAT)\n- Reclaim VAT on your business purchases (input VAT)\n- Pay the difference to HMRC every quarter\n\n## When Do You Have to Register?\n\nYou **must** register for VAT if your VAT-taxable turnover exceeds **£90,000** in any rolling 12-month period.\n\nThis is not calendar-year turnover. HMRC looks at any 12-month window — so if you had a strong 12 months between, say, April 2024 and March 2025, you''d need to register even if your calendar year figures look lower.\n\n**Important**: The threshold is based on turnover, not profit. VAT-exempt income (some financial services, insurance, health, education) doesn''t count toward the threshold.\n\n## The £90,000 Threshold: Getting It Right\n\nYou need to check your rolling 12-month turnover at the end of every month. If at any point the previous 12 months'' turnover exceeds £90,000, you must:\n\n1. Register within **30 days** of exceeding the threshold\n2. Start charging VAT from the beginning of the month **after** you registered (or the date of registration, whichever is later)\n\n**Example**: Your rolling 12-month turnover first exceeds £90,000 on 15 March 2025. You must register by 14 April 2025, and start charging VAT from 1 May 2025.\n\n## Voluntary Registration\n\nYou can register for VAT even if you''re below £90,000. Reasons to consider it:\n\n- **Reclaim input VAT**: If you have significant VATable purchases (equipment, materials, software), you can reclaim the 20% VAT — even before you hit the threshold\n- **Look more established**: Some clients (especially B2B) expect VAT-registered suppliers\n- **Flat Rate Scheme benefits** (see below)\n\nThe downside: you have to charge VAT on your sales, which can make you less competitive with non-VAT-registered competitors if you sell to consumers.\n\n## How to Register\n\n1. Go to **gov.uk/register-for-vat**\n2. Create or log in to a Government Gateway account\n3. Complete the online form (15–20 minutes)\n4. You''ll get a VAT registration number within 30 working days (often faster)\n\nWhile you''re waiting, you can charge VAT and issue VAT invoices — you just need to include your registration number when it arrives.\n\n## VAT Schemes for Small Businesses\n\n### Standard VAT Accounting\nCharge 20% VAT, reclaim VAT on purchases, pay/reclaim the net quarterly. Most straightforward but requires careful records.\n\n### Flat Rate Scheme\nFor businesses with turnover under £150,000. Instead of tracking every purchase, you pay a fixed percentage of gross turnover to HMRC.\n\nThe flat rate varies by sector:\n- IT consultants: 14.5%\n- Computer repair: 10.5%\n- Building/construction: 9.5%\n- Accountancy/bookkeeping: 14.5%\n- Retail: varies by type\n\n**How it works**: You charge customers 20% VAT, but pay HMRC a lower flat rate. The difference is your to keep.\n\n**Example (IT consultant)**: Invoice £1,000 + £200 VAT = £1,200 total. Pay HMRC 14.5% × £1,200 = £174. Keep the £26 difference.\n\n### Cash Accounting Scheme\nOnly pay VAT when you''ve actually received payment (not when you invoice). Helpful for businesses with slow-paying clients.\n\n### Annual Accounting Scheme\nMake monthly/quarterly advance payments and file one annual VAT return. Less admin.\n\n## VAT Invoices\n\nOnce VAT-registered, you must issue VAT invoices that include:\n\n- Your business name and address\n- Your VAT registration number\n- Invoice number and date\n- Description of goods/services\n- Net amount, VAT amount, and total\n- VAT rate applied\n\n## Penalties for Late Registration or Filing\n\n| Offence | Penalty |\n|---|---|\n| Late registration | Up to 15% of VAT due from late registration date |\n| Late return | Surcharge (starts at 2%, rises with repeat offences) |\n| Late payment | Interest + potential surcharge |\n\nFrom 2023, HMRC moved to a points-based penalty system for late returns. You get points for each late return; once you hit a threshold (4 points for quarterly filers), you get a £200 penalty.\n\n## Approaching the Threshold?\n\nIf you''re getting close to £90,000, use our [VAT Threshold Checker](/tools/vat-checker) to see how close you are and what your flat rate VAT bill would look like.\n\n## Do You Need an Accountant for VAT?\n\nFor most businesses, you can manage VAT yourself using accounting software (Xero, QuickBooks, FreeAgent, etc.). The returns are quarterly and take 1–2 hours once your records are in order.\n\nWhere an accountant adds value: if you have partial exemption (some exempt, some taxable sales), international transactions, or capital goods scheme assets.\n\n---\n\n*Check where you stand with our free [VAT Threshold Checker](/tools/vat-checker), or use our [Business Launchpad](/launchpad) to make sure your business setup is complete.*',
  'tax-and-finance',
  ARRAY['VAT', 'VAT registration', 'tax', 'flat rate scheme', 'HMRC'],
  'Akin Yavuz',
  true,
  now() - interval '18 days',
  'VAT Registration UK Guide — When You Must Register and How',
  'When must you register for VAT? Everything small business owners need to know about the £90,000 threshold, how to register, and the best VAT scheme for your business.',
  9
),

