-- 5. Websites and Digital
-- =============================================
(
  'why-your-small-business-needs-a-website-in-2025',
  'Why Your Small Business Still Needs a Proper Website in 2025',
  'Social media isn''t enough. Here''s why a proper website is still the best investment a local business can make — and what "proper" actually means.',
  E'## "I''ve Got Facebook — Do I Really Need a Website?"\n\nIt''s a fair question. Facebook has billions of users. Instagram is where people discover new businesses. Google My Business gets you on the map. So why pay for a website?\n\nHere''s the thing: those platforms are rented land. Facebook can change its algorithm overnight and your reach drops by 90%. Instagram can suspend your account. Google My Business can remove listings it considers spam.\n\nYour website is owned land. You control it completely.\n\n## What a Website Does That Social Media Can''t\n\n### 1. You Own the Platform\n\nNo algorithm decides who sees your content. No platform can change the rules. Your website is yours permanently — as long as you keep the domain registered.\n\n### 2. Google Search Traffic\n\nWhen someone searches "plumber in Dumfries" or "dog groomer near me," they''re actively looking to buy. That''s the highest-quality traffic you can get.\n\nA Facebook page ranks poorly in Google. A properly optimised website for "plumber Dumfries" can appear at the top of search results — and generate calls 24 hours a day without any ad spend.\n\n### 3. Credibility and Professionalism\n\nResearch consistently shows that over 75% of people judge a business''s credibility by its website design. A poor website (or no website) signals that you''re not serious about your business.\n\nFor B2B clients or higher-value projects, a professional website is often the difference between getting the job and not.\n\n### 4. You Control the Story\n\nOn social media, your posts sit alongside cat videos and political arguments. On your website, you control the entire experience. You choose what people see, in what order, and how they''re guided toward contacting you.\n\n### 5. Always Open\n\nYour website works at 2am on a Sunday. A contact form or booking system means you can capture leads while you sleep.\n\n## What Makes a Good Business Website in 2025?\n\nNot just any website — a *good* website. Here''s what that means in practice:\n\n### Fast Loading Speed\nIf your site takes more than 3 seconds to load, more than half of visitors will leave. Google also uses speed as a ranking factor.\n\n**Target**: Under 2 seconds on mobile. Use Google''s PageSpeed Insights to check.\n\n### Mobile-First Design\nOver 60% of web traffic is mobile. Your site needs to work perfectly on a 5-inch screen, with buttons big enough to tap and text that doesn''t require pinching.\n\n### Clear Call to Action\nEvery page should have one obvious next step: "Call now," "Book a free consultation," "Get a quote." Visitors who arrive but don''t know what to do will leave.\n\n### Local SEO Basics\n- Your town/city/region in the page title and headings\n- Your address in the footer\n- Google My Business linked and consistent with your website\n- Pages targeting specific services: "Boiler installation Dumfries" not just "Plumbing"\n\n### Genuine Content\nGoogle''s helpful content update rewards sites with real, useful information written for humans. Generic text that could apply to any business in any location will rank poorly.\n\nWrite about your actual services, your actual area, your actual experience.\n\n## The Cost Question\n\nA basic website can cost anywhere from £0 (DIY on Wix) to £10,000+ (bespoke agency build).\n\nFor most small local businesses, the sweet spot is **£1,500–£3,500** for a professionally designed website that:\n- Loads fast\n- Ranks well locally\n- Works on mobile\n- Has a contact form or booking system\n- Is built on a CMS you can update yourself\n\nThat''s a one-time cost. Compared to the lifetime value of even one additional customer per month, it pays for itself quickly.\n\n## What About DIY Website Builders?\n\nWix, Squarespace, and Shopify have made it easier than ever to build your own site. They''re a reasonable starting point if you:\n- Have time to learn them properly\n- Have a good eye for design\n- Are disciplined about keeping them updated\n\nThe common problems with DIY builds:\n- Generic templates that look like every other small business site\n- Poor mobile performance\n- Weak SEO by default\n- Limited customisation as your needs grow\n\nFor a business generating £50,000+ revenue, a professional website is worth the investment.\n\n## Real Results: What a Good Website Can Do\n\nOne of our clients — a plumber in Dumfries — had no website and relied entirely on word of mouth. After launching a 5-page optimised website:\n\n- First page Google ranking for "plumber Dumfries" within 3 months\n- Average of 4–6 new enquiries per week from Google search\n- Bookings consistently 6 weeks out\n\nThat''s the power of owned, search-optimised web presence.\n\n## Getting Started\n\nIf you don''t have a website yet, start here:\n\n1. Register your domain (ideally your-business-name.co.uk)\n2. Set up Google My Business\n3. Get a simple 5-page website: Home, Services, About, Contact, and one local landing page\n4. Optimise for local search\n\nNeed help? [Book a free call](/book) and we''ll talk through what would work for your specific business.\n\n---\n\n*See what we''ve built for other local businesses in the [Work](/work) section, or read about our [website packages](/services).*',
  'websites-and-digital',
  ARRAY['website', 'local business', 'SEO', 'small business', 'digital marketing'],
  'Akin Yavuz',
  true,
  now() - interval '15 days',
  'Why Your Small Business Needs a Website in 2025',
  'Social media isn''t enough for your small business. Here''s why a proper website is still your best digital investment and what a good one looks like in 2025.',
  8
),

