-- 6. Marketing
-- =============================================
(
  'google-my-business-guide-local-businesses',
  'Google My Business: The Free Tool Every Local Business Needs to Use',
  'Google My Business is the most powerful free marketing tool for local businesses — and most owners barely scratch the surface of what it can do.',
  E'## What Is Google My Business (Google Business Profile)?\n\nWhen you search for a local business — "café near me," "electrician Kirkcudbright," "accountant Dumfries" — you see a block of business listings with maps, photos, reviews, and contact details before you even see traditional website results.\n\nThat''s Google Business Profile (formerly Google My Business). It''s a free listing that puts your business directly in front of people searching for your services.\n\nFor local businesses, it''s often more valuable than a website for driving immediate calls and visits.\n\n## Why It Matters\n\nGoogle is where 93% of UK consumers start their search when looking for local services. The businesses that appear in the "Local Pack" (the map block with 3 listings) get:\n\n- Direct calls from the listing (no click required)\n- Directions requests\n- Website visits\n- Booking requests (if you set it up)\n- Review-driven trust before they even visit your site\n\nBusinesses in the Local Pack get roughly 44% of all clicks for local searches. The businesses that don''t appear there are largely invisible.\n\n## Setting Up Your Google Business Profile\n\n### Step 1: Create or Claim Your Listing\n\nGo to **google.com/business** and sign in with a Google account.\n\nSearch for your business. If it already exists (Google sometimes creates listings automatically), claim it. If not, create it from scratch.\n\n### Step 2: Complete Every Field\n\nGoogle rewards completeness. Fill in:\n\n- **Business name**: Exactly as it appears on your signage and website. Don''t stuff keywords.\n- **Category**: Choose your primary category carefully — this is the most important ranking factor. Add secondary categories too.\n- **Address**: Use your full address, even if you''re home-based (you can hide it for service-area businesses)\n- **Phone number**: Use a local number if possible\n- **Website**: Link to your website (or a specific landing page)\n- **Business hours**: Keep these accurate and update for bank holidays\n- **Service area**: If you serve a region, specify it\n\n### Step 3: Write a Good Description\n\nYou get 750 characters. Use them. Describe what you do, where you serve, and what makes you different. Include your main services and location naturally — not stuffed keyword lists.\n\n### Step 4: Upload Photos\n\nListings with photos get significantly more engagement. Add:\n- Logo and cover photo\n- Photos of your work (before/after is great for tradespeople)\n- Your premises if relevant\n- Photos of you and your team\n- Recent project photos\n\nAim for 10+ photos. Update regularly — Google notices fresh activity.\n\n### Step 5: Add Your Services\n\nIn the "Services" section, list every service you offer with a description and price range if relevant. This helps Google understand what you do and match you to relevant searches.\n\n## Getting Reviews (The Most Important Thing)\n\nReviews are the single biggest factor in Local Pack rankings after relevance and distance.\n\nBusinesses with more, better reviews rank higher and get more clicks.\n\n**How to get more reviews:**\n\n1. **Just ask**: After completing a job, text or email the client directly: "If you''re happy with the work, a Google review would really help us — here''s the link: [direct review link]"\n2. **QR code**: Print a QR code that goes directly to your review page and put it on invoices, receipts, or a card you leave behind\n3. **Reply to every review**: Both good and bad. It shows you''re engaged and builds trust\n4. **Don''t incentivise reviews**: Google prohibits offering discounts or gifts for reviews\n\nA direct review link looks like: `https://search.google.com/local/writereview?placeid=YOUR_PLACE_ID` — find your Place ID in the Google Business Profile dashboard.\n\n## Posts: The Feature Nobody Uses\n\nGoogle Business Profile lets you post updates — offers, news, events, blog posts — that appear directly on your profile in search results.\n\nHardly any small businesses use this. Which means if you do, you stand out.\n\nPost:\n- Seasonal offers and promotions\n- New services you''ve added\n- Completed project highlights\n- Useful tips for your audience\n\nPosts stay live for 7 days (events last longer), so aim to post weekly.\n\n## Answering Questions\n\nThe Q&A section on your profile lets anyone ask questions — and anyone can answer them. That includes your competitors and random internet users.\n\nMonitor your Q&A and answer questions promptly with accurate information. You can also proactively add common questions yourself.\n\n## Tracking Performance\n\nGoogle Business Profile has built-in analytics showing:\n- How many people found you (search vs maps)\n- What search queries triggered your listing\n- How many people called, clicked for directions, or visited your website\n\nCheck these monthly. If calls are low despite good impressions, your profile might need better photos or more reviews.\n\n## Common Mistakes\n\n1. **Inconsistent NAP**: Your Name, Address, Phone must be identical on Google, your website, and every directory. Inconsistency hurts rankings.\n2. **Old hours**: Nothing worse than a customer arriving when you''re closed because your Google listing was wrong.\n3. **No photos**: Listings without photos get dramatically less engagement.\n4. **Ignoring reviews**: Not responding to reviews (especially negative ones) looks unprofessional.\n5. **Wrong category**: The wrong primary category can mean you never appear for your core service searches.\n\n## The Bigger Picture\n\nGoogle Business Profile is free and it works. Set it up properly, keep it updated, and actively collect reviews — and you''ll outrank most of your local competition within a few months.\n\nPair it with a well-optimised website and you''re covering both sides of local search: the map pack and the organic results.\n\n---\n\n*Need help setting up your Google Business Profile or building a website that ranks locally? [Book a free call](/book) and we''ll take a look at your current setup.*',
  'marketing',
  ARRAY['Google My Business', 'local SEO', 'marketing', 'local business', 'reviews'],
  'Akin Yavuz',
  true,
  now() - interval '12 days',
  'Google My Business Guide for Local Businesses — 2025',
  'Google My Business is the most powerful free marketing tool for local businesses. Learn how to set it up properly, get reviews, and rank in local search results.',
  10
),

-- =============================================
-- 7. Tools and Resources
-- =============================================
(
  'best-free-tools-for-uk-sole-traders',
  '10 Free Tools Every UK Sole Trader Should Be Using',
  'Running a business doesn''t mean spending a fortune on software. These free (or freemium) tools cover invoicing, accounting, communication, and more.',
  E'## You Don''t Need to Spend Much to Run a Business Well\n\nWhen you''re starting out, or keeping overheads tight, the good news is that some of the best business tools are free — or have generous free tiers that cover everything a sole trader needs.\n\nHere are 10 I''d recommend, categorised by what they do.\n\n## Accounting and Invoicing\n\n### 1. FreeAgent (via NatWest/RBS)\nIf you bank with NatWest or RBS, you get FreeAgent free. It''s full-featured cloud accounting software — invoicing, expense tracking, Self Assessment filing, VAT returns. Worth knowing about even if you switch banks for it.\n\n**Best for**: Sole traders who want proper accounting without the monthly cost\n\n### 2. Wave\nWave is genuinely free for invoicing and accounting (no hidden tier limits). You can create professional invoices, track income and expenses, and connect your bank. Payments are extra, but the core tool is free.\n\n**Best for**: Freelancers and consultants with simple finances\n\n### 3. Pandle\nA UK-based free accounting tool built specifically for small businesses. Simpler than Xero or QuickBooks, which makes it approachable if you''re not an accountant.\n\n**Best for**: Tradespeople and service businesses new to bookkeeping\n\n## Communication\n\n### 4. Google Workspace (Free Tier)\nGmail, Google Docs, Sheets, Drive, Meet, Calendar — all free with a personal Google account. For professional emails, you''ll want a custom domain (use Workspace Business Starter at £6/month), but the free tier handles most needs.\n\n**Best for**: Document creation, sharing, and video calls\n\n### 5. Slack (Free)\nSlack''s free tier lets you communicate with a small team or contractors, integrate basic apps, and keep 90 days of message history. If you work with subcontractors or have virtual assistants, this is cleaner than email.\n\n**Best for**: Businesses with small remote teams\n\n## Productivity and Project Management\n\n### 6. Trello (Free)\nTrello''s Kanban-style boards are brilliant for tracking projects, managing client work, or keeping on top of leads. The free tier has unlimited cards and up to 10 boards.\n\n**Best for**: Managing client projects and to-do lists visually\n\n### 7. Notion (Free for Personal Use)\nNotion combines notes, databases, wikis, and project management. Use it to store client briefs, track leads, write SOPs, or create a knowledge base for your business.\n\n**Best for**: Knowledge workers who want everything in one place\n\n## Marketing\n\n### 8. Canva (Free Tier)\nProfessional-looking graphics without a designer. Canva''s free tier has thousands of templates for social media, presentations, flyers, business cards, and more. Drag-and-drop, no design experience needed.\n\n**Best for**: Creating consistent, professional social media content\n\n### 9. Mailchimp (Free up to 500 contacts)\nEmail marketing — send newsletters, automate welcome sequences, track opens and clicks. The free tier handles up to 500 contacts and 1,000 monthly emails. More than enough for a starting business.\n\n**Best for**: Staying in touch with clients and building an email list\n\n## Tax and Finance\n\n### 10. HMRC''s Business Tax Account\nFree, official, and essential. Log in at gov.uk to file your Self Assessment, check your NI record, manage PAYE if you have employees, and view any outstanding tax.\n\n**Best for**: All sole traders — this is required, not optional\n\n## Bonus: Nith Digital''s Free Tools\n\nWe''ve also built a few free calculators specifically for UK sole traders and small businesses:\n\n- **[Take-Home Pay Calculator](/tools/take-home-calculator)** — Calculate your actual take-home after income tax, NI, and student loan\n- **[VAT Threshold Checker](/tools/vat-checker)** — See how close you are to the VAT threshold\n- **[Sole Trader vs Limited Company Calculator](/tools/sole-trader-vs-limited)** — Compare the tax difference at your profit level\n- **[LBTT Calculator](/tools/lbtt-calculator)** — Scottish Land and Buildings Transaction Tax for property purchases\n- **[Invoice Generator](/tools/invoice-generator)** — Create professional invoices and download as PDF, free\n\n## A Note on "Free"\n\nMost of these tools have paid tiers that unlock more features. As your business grows, it''s worth paying for tools that save you significant time or reduce errors.\n\nBut for a sole trader just starting out or running a lean operation, these free tools are genuinely capable — not watered-down demos.\n\n---\n\n*If you''re just getting started, our [Business Launchpad](/launchpad) walks you through everything you need to set up a proper business from scratch — including which tools to use at each stage.*',
  'tools-and-resources',
  ARRAY['free tools', 'sole trader', 'software', 'accounting', 'productivity'],
  'Akin Yavuz',
  true,
  now() - interval '10 days',
  '10 Free Tools Every UK Sole Trader Should Be Using',
  'The best free tools for UK sole traders: free invoicing software, accounting tools, project management, and marketing tools to run your business without breaking the bank.',
  7
),

-- =============================================
-- 8. Local Business
-- =============================================
(
  'marketing-local-business-dumfries-galloway',
  'How to Market a Local Business in Dumfries and Galloway',
  'Marketing in a rural area is different from marketing in a city. Here''s what actually works for local businesses in D&G.',
  E'## The Unique Challenge of Rural Marketing\n\nMarketing a business in Dumfries and Galloway isn''t the same as marketing in Glasgow or Edinburgh. The population is spread across a large geographic area, competition can be thin but trust networks are tight, and word of mouth carries more weight than anywhere.\n\nThis creates a different set of priorities for local marketing.\n\n## What Works in D&G\n\n### 1. Google Search — Your #1 Lead Generator\n\nDespite the rural context, Google is still where most people start when looking for a tradesperson, professional service, or local shop.\n\n"Plumber Sanquhar," "web designer Dumfries," "accountant Castle Douglas" — these are low-competition keywords compared to city equivalents, which means it''s relatively easier to rank on the first page.\n\n**What to do:**\n- Set up and fully complete your Google Business Profile\n- Build a website with pages targeting your specific services and locations\n- Collect Google reviews consistently\n\n### 2. Word of Mouth — Still King\n\nD&G has strong community networks. When someone in Thornhill needs a builder, they ask their neighbours before they Google. When a business in Lockerbie needs a bookkeeper, they ask their accountant who they know.\n\n**How to harness it:**\n- Do excellent work and actively ask happy clients to refer you\n- Attend local networking events (Chamber of Commerce, BNI, sector-specific groups)\n- Be visible in local community groups on Facebook (there are active ones for most towns)\n- Ask for referrals directly — most clients will happily send work your way if asked\n\n### 3. Facebook Groups and Pages\n\nFor consumer-facing businesses, Facebook is particularly effective in rural areas where the demographic skews older than TikTok or Instagram audiences.\n\nKey D&G Facebook communities are active and businesses that engage authentically (not just posting ads) build real followings.\n\n**What works:**\n- Completed project photos with location mentioned\n- Helpful tips relevant to your trade\n- Responding quickly to enquiries in comments\n- Posting in local community groups where allowed\n\n### 4. Nextdoor\n\nNextdoor is an underused gem for local service businesses. It''s a neighbourhood social network where people ask for and give recommendations. Get verified as a business and respond to recommendation requests in your service area.\n\n### 5. Local Press and Radio\n\nDumfries & Galloway Standard, Galloway News, and South West Sound still have meaningful reach — particularly among the 40+ demographic that makes up a significant portion of D&G''s population and a lot of purchasing power.\n\nA story about a business opening, a charity event, or an interesting project can generate real coverage. Local press are generally receptive to genuine stories from local businesses.\n\n### 6. Networking\n\n- **D&G Chamber of Commerce**: Monthly networking events across the region\n- **Business Gateway D&G**: Free support and events for local businesses\n- **Federation of Small Businesses**: National body with local networking\n- **Sector-specific groups**: Tourism, agriculture, construction — most have their own networks\n\nIn a tight-knit community, who you know matters. Showing up consistently builds the kind of trust that generates referrals.\n\n### 7. Seasonal and Tourism Marketing\n\nD&G attracts significant visitor numbers, particularly during the summer and around events like the Wickerman Festival (historically), agricultural shows, and Christmas markets.\n\nIf you serve tourists or seasonal visitors:\n- List on VisitScotland\n- Appear on local tourism websites\n- Partner with accommodation providers\n- Update your Google Business Profile with relevant seasonal info\n\n## What Doesn''t Work as Well\n\n**Instagram and TikTok**: Lower engagement for most service businesses in D&G compared to Glasgow. Not useless, but not the priority.\n\n**Paid Google Ads**: Can be effective, but competition for D&G searches is low enough that organic/GMB often beats paid for cost-effectiveness.\n\n**Leaflet drops**: Still used but declining effectiveness. Better for highly targeted geographic campaigns (new housing developments, specific postcodes) than blanket coverage.\n\n## Budget and Priorities\n\nFor a local D&G business with limited marketing budget, I''d suggest this priority order:\n\n1. **Google Business Profile**: Free, highest ROI, do this first\n2. **Website with local SEO**: One-time cost, ongoing organic traffic\n3. **Consistent review collection**: Ongoing, free, builds credibility\n4. **Facebook presence**: Free, maintain regularly\n5. **Networking**: Time investment, long-term payoff\n\nWith this foundation, most local service businesses can generate a steady flow of enquiries without significant paid advertising.\n\n## Getting Help\n\nNith Digital is based in the region and builds websites and digital tools for local businesses across D&G. We understand the local market because we''re in it.\n\n[Book a free call](/book) to talk through your business''s marketing and what would work for your specific situation.\n\n---\n\n*Also worth reading: [Why Your Small Business Needs a Proper Website in 2025](/blog/why-your-small-business-needs-a-website-in-2025)*',
  'local-business',
  ARRAY['Dumfries and Galloway', 'local marketing', 'small business', 'Scotland', 'rural business'],
  'Akin Yavuz',
  true,
  now() - interval '8 days',
  'How to Market a Local Business in Dumfries and Galloway',
  'Marketing strategies that actually work for local businesses in Dumfries and Galloway: from Google Business Profile to community networking and local press.',
  9
),

