-- 9. Websites and Digital
-- =============================================
(
  'what-does-a-website-cost-small-business-uk',
  'What Should a Small Business Website Actually Cost in 2025?',
  'Website prices range from free to £20,000+. Here''s what you actually need and what you should expect to pay for it.',
  E'## The Range Is Enormous\n\nAsk five agencies what a website costs and you''ll get five very different answers. Everything from "£500 done" to "£15,000 starting from." Both can be legitimate. Neither is automatically right for your business.\n\nHere''s how to understand what''s behind the price and what you should actually be paying for your situation.\n\n## The Three Categories of Small Business Website\n\n### Category 1: DIY Website (£0–£250/year)\n\nTools like Wix, Squarespace, and GoDaddy Website Builder let you build something yourself for minimal cost.\n\n**What you get**: A functional website with a template design, basic pages, contact form, mobile-responsive layout.\n\n**What you don''t get**: A design that stands out, proper SEO configuration, fast loading speeds, or a site that grows with your business.\n\n**Best for**: Sole traders testing an idea, businesses with very limited budgets, people who enjoy learning new tools.\n\n**Hidden costs**: Your time (significant if you''re not tech-savvy), the cost of looking generic, lost leads from slow or poor-quality sites.\n\n### Category 2: Budget Professional Build (£800–£2,500)\n\nFreelancers and small agencies building WordPress or similar CMS sites at competitive prices.\n\n**What you get**: Professional design, proper mobile experience, basic on-page SEO, contact form, CMS so you can update content.\n\n**What you don''t get**: Custom functionality, deep SEO strategy, conversion optimisation, or significant ongoing support.\n\n**Best for**: Small businesses with 5–15 pages of content, simple services, no complex functionality needs.\n\n**Watch out for**: Very cheap builds often use low-quality themes and plugins that create security and performance problems. Ask to see examples of their previous work.\n\n### Category 3: Professional Build with Strategy (£3,000–£8,000)\n\nExperienced freelancers or small agencies who do proper discovery work, strategic design, and thorough development.\n\n**What you get**: A site built around your business goals, proper technical SEO, conversion-focused design, custom elements, thorough testing, and typically some level of ongoing support.\n\n**Best for**: Established businesses where the website is a primary sales tool, businesses wanting to rank well in competitive local searches.\n\n### Category 4: Agency Build (£8,000+)\n\nLarge agencies with teams of specialists. Appropriate for larger businesses with complex needs, ecommerce stores, or platforms requiring significant custom development.\n\n**Best for**: Companies where the website underpins significant revenue and the budget can justify specialist teams.\n\n## What Should You Actually Pay?\n\nFor most local service businesses in the UK — tradespeople, professional services, B&Bs, shops — the sweet spot is **£1,500–£4,000**.\n\nAt this budget, you get:\n- A professional, custom-feeling design (not obviously a template)\n- Fast loading speeds\n- Proper mobile experience\n- On-page SEO that actually gives you a chance of ranking\n- 5–10 pages\n- Contact form or basic booking integration\n- 1–2 hours of training to manage the site yourself\n\n## Questions to Ask Before Hiring Anyone\n\n1. **Can I see examples of previous work?** — And are those sites actually live? Check the Google Page Speed score on their examples.\n\n2. **Who owns the website?** — You should own the domain and hosting contract. Avoid arrangements where the developer "owns" the site and charges you monthly to keep it live.\n\n3. **What platform will it be built on?** — WordPress, Squarespace, Webflow, and custom builds all have different implications for ongoing costs and control.\n\n4. **What''s included after launch?** — Some developers offer 3–6 months of support. Others charge immediately for any changes.\n\n5. **How will it be hosted, and what does that cost?** — Hosting typically costs £5–£25/month. Some developers bundle this at inflated rates.\n\n6. **Will I be able to update it myself?** — If you need to change a price or add a service, can you do that without calling the developer?\n\n## Ongoing Costs to Budget For\n\nA website isn''t just a one-time expense:\n\n| Cost | Typical Annual Amount |\n|---|---|\n| Domain (.co.uk) | £10–£20/year |\n| Hosting | £60–£240/year |\n| SSL certificate | Often free (Let''s Encrypt) or included |\n| Maintenance/updates | £150–£500/year if using a developer |\n| Content updates | Your time, or £50–£150 per page |\n\n## The Real ROI Question\n\nThe right question isn''t "how much does a website cost?" — it''s "what is a new client worth to me?"\n\nIf an average client is worth £2,000, and a properly built website generates 2 additional clients per month from Google search, that''s £48,000 in annual revenue from a £3,000 investment.\n\nIn that context, the website cost is trivial. Invest in the quality that generates the traffic and the conversions.\n\n---\n\n*Nith Digital builds professional websites for local businesses in Dumfries and Galloway, starting from £1,500. [Book a free call](/book) to discuss your project.*',
  'websites-and-digital',
  ARRAY['website cost', 'web design', 'small business', 'UK', 'budget'],
  'Akin Yavuz',
  true,
  now() - interval '6 days',
  'What Should a Small Business Website Cost in 2025?',
  'Website prices range from free to £20,000+. This guide explains what each budget gets you and what a local small business should actually spend to get results.',
  8
),

